         </head>
         <body view="all">
            <ce:sections>
               <ce:section id="sec0005" role="introduction" view="all">
                  <ce:label>1</ce:label>
                  <ce:section-title id="sect0025">Introduction</ce:section-title>
                  <ce:para id="p0030" view="all">Biodiversity, especially tree species diversity, is a basis of forest ecosystem health, resilience, and sustainability (<ce:cross-refs id="crs0005" refid="bib10 bib5">Brockerhoff et al., 2017; Bai et al., 2024</ce:cross-refs>). In old-growth forests (OGF), which represent one of the most complex and undisturbed ecosystems on Earth, biodiversity plays an even more critical role. These forests are characterized by their rich species composition, structural complexity, and long ecological background, making them vital reservoirs of genetic, species, and functional diversity (<ce:cross-refs id="crs0010" refid="bib54 bib66">Mosseler et al., 2003; Spies, 2004</ce:cross-refs>). Tree species diversity in OGFs contributes to the overall resilience of these ecosystems, helping them withstand and recover from environmental stressors, such as climate change, pest outbreaks, and natural disturbances such as fire or storm (<ce:cross-refs id="crs0015" refid="bib58 bib21">Price et al., 2020; Czerepko et al., 2021</ce:cross-refs>). The presence of diverse tree species supports a range of ecological processes essential for forest function. For example, species diversity promotes nutrient cycling, enhances soil fertility, and regulates water balance, all of which are crucial for sustaining forest health. Moreover, a variety of tree species provides habitats for other organisms, supporting a rich web of life that includes plants, animals, fungi, and microorganisms (<ce:cross-refs id="crs0020" refid="bib35 bib18">Gilhen-Baker et al., 2022; Chen et al., 2023</ce:cross-refs>). In the era of global environmental change, OGFs with high species diversity are more capable to adapt to shifting conditions, as the presence of multiple species increases the likelihood that some species will be well-suited to the new environmental condition. This adaptive capacity is crucial for maintaining ecosystem services, such as air and water purification, timber production, and recreation opportunities, which are essential not only for local communities but also for global environmental health (<ce:cross-refs id="crs0025" refid="bib32 bib53 bib8">Gamfeldt et al., 2013; Mori et al., 2017; Barros et al., 2022</ce:cross-refs>). Given the ecological, economic, and cultural importance of OGFs, understanding and monitoring their biodiversity is essential.</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0035" view="all">Traditional field observations have long underpinned biodiversity assessment and monitoring, but they face significant challenges. Field surveys are labor-intensive, time-consuming, and require extensive resources, making it difficult to capture species diversity across large, remote, or inaccessible areas. They also tend to be localized, providing detailed information on small plots but lacking the broader context needed to assess biodiversity across larger landscapes. Consequently, field observations may fail to capture large-scale, dynamic changes critical for understanding ecosystem health over time (<ce:cross-refs id="crs0030" refid="bib3 bib19 bib24">Asner and Martin, 2011; Chrysafis et al., 2020; Erfanifard et al., 2024</ce:cross-refs>). To address these limitations, remote sensing has emerged as a valuable tool in ecological research, offering efficient biodiversity monitoring across vast areas. Remote sensing technologies, such as airborne and satellite imagery, gather continuous data over large areas at the same timepoint, eliminating the need for interpolation required with discrete sampling methods. These technologies enable the collection of detailed information on forest composition, canopy structure, and species diversity over broad spatial and temporal scales. This capability is particularly valuable for studying biodiversity changes in response to climate change, disturbances, or management practices (<ce:cross-refs id="crs0035" refid="bib43 bib25 bib37 bib42 bib6">Jetz et al., 2016; Erfanifard et al., 2019; Gyamfi-Ampadu et al., 2021; Immitzer and Atzberger, 2023; Ball et al., 2024</ce:cross-refs>).</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0040" view="all">In general, two main approaches have been implemented for remote sensing-based tree species diversity assessment. The indirect approach, which has gained significant attention in recent years, involves developing models that correlate observable parameters from remote sensing data with biodiversity indices derived from field observations (<ce:cross-refs id="crs0040" refid="bib2 bib14 bib47 bib50">Asner et al., 2017; Cazzolla Gatti et al., 2017; Laliberté et al., 2020; Mashiane et al., 2024</ce:cross-refs>). This approach, while established, continues to evolve with advancements in remote sensing technology, making it an innovative and increasingly valuable tool for biodiversity assessments (<ce:cross-refs id="crs0045" refid="bib62 bib20 bib70">Rocchini et al., 2010; Coops and Wulder, 2019; Torresani et al., 2024</ce:cross-refs>). Studies like those by <ce:cross-ref id="cr0055" refid="bib61">Rocchini (2007)</ce:cross-ref> and <ce:cross-ref id="cr0060" refid="bib77">Xi et al. (2024)</ce:cross-ref> have demonstrated how satellite data can effectively model biodiversity patterns in forest ecosystems. While these models capture canopy-level characteristics, challenges remain in accurately representing species diversity, especially with medium to low-resolution datasets. For the indirect approach, low resolution can lead to mixed signals when each pixel represents multiple trees, making species differentiation difficult. However, with higher-resolution data, these challenges can be mitigated (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0065" refid="bib30">Féret and Asner, 2014</ce:cross-ref>). Additionally, the approach is not limited to spectral data alone; they can also integrate structural data from sources like Airborne Laser Scanning (ALS) to provide more detailed models of tree species diversity (<ce:cross-refs id="crs0050" refid="bib68 bib70">Toivonen et al., 2023; Torresani et al., 2024</ce:cross-refs>). ALS, which captures canopy structure, has been used in studies such as those by <ce:cross-ref id="cr0070" refid="bib36">Goodbody et al. (2020)</ce:cross-ref> and <ce:cross-ref id="cr0075" refid="bib56">Murray et al. (2024)</ce:cross-ref> to predict species richness and composition more effectively. While the indirect approach provides valuable insights into biodiversity patterns, the emerging method of correlating species diversity with spectral and structural diversity using datasets of varying resolutions (low, medium, and high) is rapidly advancing (<ce:cross-refs id="crs0055" refid="bib61 bib30 bib77">Rocchini, 2007; Féret and Asner, 2014; Xi et al., 2024</ce:cross-refs>). This approach, effective for fine- and large-scale biodiversity assessments, is increasingly employing spectral variability and structural metrics to offer a more comprehensive understanding of biodiversity. As the technology evolves, it holds significant promise for enhancing biodiversity monitoring across diverse forest types and regions.</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0045" view="all">While the indirect approach has gained significant attention in recent years and is applicable to remote sensing datasets ranging from low to high spatial resolutions, another strategy, the direct approach, has been in use for some time. This approach involves directly mapping tree species from high-resolution remote sensing (RS) datasets, which are capable of capturing individual trees. From this, biodiversity metrics can be directly calculated, eliminating the need for models that rely on remote sensing-field correlations. In general, this approach struggles due to the limitations of low spatial resolution, limited coverage, and the high costs of RS data, making it challenging to assess fine-scale species diversity effectively (<ce:cross-refs id="crs0060" refid="bib27 bib49">Fassnacht et al., 2016; Liu et al., 2024</ce:cross-refs>). However, with the recent availability of lower-cost RS datasets, particularly from airborne and drone platforms (<ce:cross-refs id="crs0065" refid="bib41 bib71">Huang et al., 2024; Ullah et al., 2025</ce:cross-refs>), this approach has become more viable. Additionally, recent advances in machine learning and deep learning algorithms now enable direct species identification from RS data. While early work by <ce:cross-ref id="cr0080" refid="bib29">Féret and Asner (2013)</ce:cross-ref> demonstrated the potential of high-resolution imagery for mapping individual tree species, the direct use of RS-based species maps for species diversity assessment has remained less explored in the literature. Challenges still exist, particularly in their ability to capture understory species, which are critical for comprehensive biodiversity assessments (<ce:cross-refs id="crs0070" refid="bib30 bib63 bib46 bib68">Féret and Asner, 2014; Rocchini et al., 2022; Kostensalo et al., 2023; Toivonen et al., 2023</ce:cross-refs>). Moreover, accurate species identification requires labeled datasets and advanced computational tools, making it resource-intensive and technically demanding (<ce:cross-refs id="crs0075" refid="bib75 bib41">Xi et al., 2021; Huang et al., 2024</ce:cross-refs>). The effectiveness of this approach also depends on the correlation between canopy and understory diversity, which, although theoretically strong (<ce:cross-refs id="crs0080" refid="bib13 bib9">Cavard et al., 2011; Bohlman, 2015</ce:cross-refs>), can be influenced by factors such as canopy cover, tree basal area, management practices and species composition (<ce:cross-refs id="crs0085" refid="bib7 bib24">Barbier et al., 2009; Erfanifard et al., 2024</ce:cross-refs>). Nonetheless, with the growing availability of RS data and the potential for their fusion, this approach presents an exciting opportunity for further research, offering the ability to directly assess tree-level biodiversity with high precision, despite the remaining challenges.</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0050" view="all">The direct approach has the potential to provide biodiversity assessments at fine spatial scales by enabling species-level identification from RS data. Despite advancements in machine learning and sensor technology, their application remains less explored, particularly in complex environments such as OGFs. Addressing this gap, our research evaluates RS-based biodiversity assessment methods while considering both canopy and understory species. By directly comparing RS estimates with field observations, we assess their accuracy in OGFs, which exhibit complex spatial and temporal dynamics. Additionally, our study incorporates stratification by different species compositions and forest management strategies; factors rarely explored; that further enhance our understanding of how these stratifications influence the direct approach. For instance, forests under different management strategies may exhibit varying structural complexities, affecting the ability of RS data to explore species diversity effectively. Similarly, the species composition in broadleaved, coniferous, or mixed forests could influence classification accuracy and the derived biodiversity indices. While our RS-based direct approach focuses on canopy species, the inclusion of understory species in field observations underscores the potential underestimation of diversity due to the limited ability of such techniques to detect species beneath the canopy. This is acknowledged in our methodology, where we discuss how structural variables from LiDAR can aid in better classifying canopy species, but the challenge of not distinguishing understory species remains.</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0055" view="all">The primary objective of this study is to examine how RS data can effectively capture tree species diversity dynamics within canopy layers across various spatial scales. Specifically, we aim to address two hypotheses. Hypothesis 1 (H1) assumes that RS will provide significant insights into the species diversity of canopy tree across varying spatial contexts, suggesting that it can be a valuable tool for ecological monitoring in such species-rich habitats as OGFs. Hypothesis 2 (H2) suggests a strong correlation between estimates of biodiversity from RS and field observations of all trees (i.e., the species diversity of both canopy and understory), with the degree of correlation expected to vary based on species compositions and forest management strategies. In broadleaved forests and strict reserves, where vertical structure and species richness are typically more complex, the potential for RS to fully capture biodiversity patterns, particularly in the understory, may be limited. In contrast, managed and mixed forests, shaped by human intervention and often characterized by more uniform or simplified structures, may present conditions where RS more closely aligns with field observations of tree diversity. Our research will derive biodiversity indices directly from RS data, integrating advancements in RS technologies and methodologies to enhance biodiversity assessments in OGFs.</ce:para>
               </ce:section>
               <ce:section id="sec0010" role="materials-methods" view="all">
                  <ce:label>2</ce:label>
                  <ce:section-title id="sect0030">Materials and methods</ce:section-title>
                  <ce:section id="sec0015" view="all">
                     <ce:label>2.1</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="sect0035">Study area</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="p0060" view="all">The Białowieża Forest (BF) was selected as the study area to evaluate the hypotheses being examined in this research. Its unique ecological characteristics, coupled with its status as a UNESCO World Natural Heritage Site, make it an ideal location for examining the reliability of RS in assessing tree species diversity and understanding how management strategies and stand compositions influence this reliability. As one of the most significant OGFs in Europe, the BF spans the Central European mixed forest ecoregion and features a remarkable mixture of pure and mixed stands of coniferous and broadleaved species. The forest encompasses various types: coniferous forests (52 %), wet broadleaved forests (20 %), mesic rich broadleaved forests (15 %), and successional stands (13 %). Home to 35 tree and shrub species (33 broadleaved and 2 coniferous), the BF preserves remnants of the primeval forest in the Białowieża National Park, highlighting its exceptional biodiversity and ecological importance. The BF is divided into three management categories, i.e., Strict Reserves (SR), Nature Reserves (NR), and Managed Forests (MF). In addition to these categories, its diverse species compositions provide a multifaceted environment to investigate the influence of varying management categories and species compositions on RS performance in biodiversity assessments.</ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
                  <ce:section id="sec0020" view="all">
                     <ce:label>2.2</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="sect0040">Field measurements</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="p0065" view="all">The study area is a transboundary OGF spanning approximately 600 km<ce:sup loc="post">2</ce:sup> across the Polish-Belarusian border. The Polish portion, which is the focus of this study, is divided into three primary categories: (i) SR, covering 47 km<ce:sup loc="post">2</ce:sup>, (ii) NR, spanning 170 km<ce:sup loc="post">2</ce:sup>, and (iii) MF, accounting for 383 km<ce:sup loc="post">2</ce:sup>. These categories represent a gradient of management strategies, ranging from untouched sites in SR to limited timber harvesting in MF (<ce:float-anchor refid="fig0005"/>
                        <ce:cross-ref id="cr0085" refid="fig0005">Fig. 1</ce:cross-ref>). The BF hosts a diverse mix of species, ranging from dominant to rarely occurring, as noted by <ce:cross-ref id="cr0090" refid="bib11">Brzeziecki et al. (2023)</ce:cross-ref>, with towering specimens exceeding 40 m in height and 1 m in diameter at breast height (DBH). This diversity underscores its importance as a biodiversity hotspot.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0070" view="all">To evaluate the hypotheses proposed in this study, we used data collected from 330 circular sample plots (each with an area of 500 m² and a radius of 12.62 m) (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0095" refid="fig0005">Fig. 1</ce:cross-ref>). These permanent plots were established as part of long-term monitoring efforts over the last decade, ensuring consistency in data collection and allowing for temporal comparisons. The chosen plot size (500 m²) aligns with standard forest inventory methods, balancing practical constraints with the need for representative biodiversity assessments. The plots were distributed equitably across the management categories, with plot densities of approximately 0.0055 plots/ha for SR (26 plots), 0.0054 plots/ha for NR (91 plots), and 0.0056 plots/ha for MF (213 plots), ensuring balanced sampling. Plots were classified into three stand types based on tree species composition: Broadleaved Stands (BS) (114 plots, 34.5 %), Coniferous Stands (CS) (106 plots, 32.1 %), and Mixed Stands (MS) (110 plots, 33.4 %). Plots with &gt; 75 % basal area of broadleaved or coniferous species were categorized as BS or CS, respectively, while MS included plots with no dominant (&gt;75 %) coniferous or broadleaved species.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0075" view="all">Field measurements (FM) conducted between October 2021 to May 2022 included a detailed tree-level inventory, recording species, visibility, height, and DBH for trees with DBH ≥ 7 cm. This inventory encompassed all trees, both living and dead, to provide a comprehensive assessment of the forest structure. Tree visibility was categorized into three levels based on their detectability in RS data from an aerial perspective: 1 for fully visible dominant and codominant trees, 2 for partially visible intermediate trees, and 3 for suppressed trees not visible in RS data. Both living and dead trees were categorized using these visibility codes, depending on their detectability from an aerial perspective. FM focused on both understory trees with visibility code 3 and canopy trees with visibility codes 1 and 2, which were also analyzed using RS data.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0080" view="all">Comprehensive spatial data were collected, including precise plot center coordinates measured via RTK (Real-Time Kinematic) and GNSS (Global Navigation Satellite System) tools (RMSE = 0.096 m), supplemented by distance and azimuth measurements for individual trees. This rigorous approach facilitated integration with RS data for canopy-level analyses and builds upon previous studies that employed active and passive RS datasets to produce detailed species maps. These methods provide a robust foundation for investigating how management strategies and stand compositions influence biodiversity within the BF.</ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
                  <ce:section id="sec0025" view="all">
                     <ce:label>2.3</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="sect0045">High-resolution remote sensing</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="p0085" view="all">In this research, individual-level species maps were generated by combining ALS and Color Infrared (CIR) datasets using the XGBoost algorithm. The leaf-on ALS data was collected in October 2022 with a Riegl VQ-780ii scanner, achieving an average point cloud density of approximately 48 points per square meter. This ALS dataset was utilized to produce digital terrain models (DTM) and digital surface models (DSM) at a resolution of 0.5 m. From these models, a normalized digital surface model (nDSM) was derived, serving as the foundation for segmenting individual canopy trees. The segmentation process employed a marker-controlled watershed algorithm, a method frequently cited in prior research (<ce:cross-refs id="crs0090" refid="bib26 bib67 bib48">Erfanifard et al., 2018; Stereńczak et al., 2020; Lisiewicz et al., 2025</ce:cross-refs>). Simultaneously, CIR images were acquired using an UltraCam Eagle M3 Camera during aerial surveys conducted at altitudes approx. 4000 m, yielding a ground sampling distance (GSD) of 0.20 m.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0090" view="all">In this study, a wide range of classification features was extracted from the ALS and CIR datasets, comprising 34 structural features, 13 intensity features, and 8 spectral features, as outlined in Table A.1. A multi-stage feature selection process was implemented, combining the feature importance rankings obtained from the XGBoost Feature Importance function (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0100" refid="bib17">Chen and Guestrin, 2016</ce:cross-ref>) with correlation-based filtering. Initially, subsets of features were evaluated using the XGBoost algorithm to compute feature importance scores, which helped identify the most significant predictors within each feature category. These top-ranked features from all categories were then merged into a single pool. To address redundancy and mitigate the risk of overfitting due to multicollinearity, a pairwise correlation analysis was performed using the Pearson correlation coefficient. Starting with the feature of highest importance, any other predictor with a correlation coefficient exceeding 0.9 relative to it was excluded. This iterative filtering process was repeated until no remaining feature pair exhibited a correlation above the threshold. The final output was a streamlined, non-redundant feature set that balanced predictive accuracy with reduced dimensionality and minimized redundant information. Details of the selected features are provided in Table A.2.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0095" view="all">For the classification of living and dead tree species (Table A.3), the XGBoost algorithm (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0105" refid="bib17">Chen and Guestrin, 2016</ce:cross-ref>) was employed using default hyperparameter settings as provided in the xgboost package for the R environment (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0110" refid="bib59">R Core Team, 2024</ce:cross-ref>). The parameters included a maximum tree depth of 6, a learning rate (eta) of 0.3, and 100 boosting rounds. The “multi:softmax” objective was used to facilitate multi-class classification, corresponding to the various tree species and classes identified in the canopy layer within the study area. To ensure robust performance evaluation and accurate classification metrics, a 5-fold cross-validation strategy was implemented, repeated 10 times. For each fold, the model was trained on a designated training subset and evaluated on the corresponding held-out test subset. This repeated procedure mitigated the influence of any particular data split, enabling more reliable and stable accuracy estimates. The average classification metrics from the cross-validation process were computed to reduce sensitivity to overfitting and to provide a comprehensive assessment of model performance. Final classification results were evaluated using key performance metrics, including the Area Under the Curve (AUC) of the Receiver Operating Characteristic (ROC) and the F1. These metrics offered critical insights into the accuracy and reliability of the species map derived from the ALS and CIR datasets.</ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
                  <ce:section id="sec0030" view="all">
                     <ce:label>2.4</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="sect0050">Methodology</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="p0100" view="all">A multi-phase methodology for assessing tree species diversity is illustrated in <ce:float-anchor refid="fig0010"/>
                        <ce:cross-ref id="cr0115" refid="fig0010">Fig. 2</ce:cross-ref>, comparing RS data with FM. The study aims to determine the reliability of RS for estimating species diversity, beginning with a focus on canopy trees and later extending to encompass all trees observed in the field. Phase 1 centers on creating a detailed map of canopy trees using RS data. This involves combining ALS data and CIR images.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0105" view="all">Specifically, the integration of ALS and CIR data is performed by assigning spectral values from the CIR images to individual tree canopy segments derived from ALS data; more precisely, from the nDSM, which is a product of ALS processing. This spatial correspondence between the ALS-derived canopy segments and the georeferenced CIR imagery enabled the extraction of spectral features from the CIR data and structural features from the ALS data for each segmented tree crown. These combined features formed the input for the subsequent classification process. By applying the XGBoost algorithm to the combined feature set, a map of tree species at the canopy level is generated and subsequently validated with FM. This foundational phase establishes an accurate canopy map, which serves as the basis for comparing tree species diversity captured in RS versus FM. Phase 2 tests the H1 that RS can reliably assess canopy tree species diversity. Field-identified canopy trees are compared with those detected via RS, using Hill numbers to measure diversity: Richness (<ce:italic>q</ce:italic>=0), Shannon diversity (<ce:italic>q</ce:italic>=1), and Simpson or dominance-weighted diversity (<ce:italic>q</ce:italic>=2), capturing unique species, abundance, and dominance. Correlation, Bland-Altman agreement, and Bray-Curtis dissimilarity coefficient were implemented to evaluate agreement and discrepancies between RS and field data. This phase examines the accuracy of RS in capturing canopy tree diversity compared with FM. Phase 3 tests the H2 that RS can assess tree species diversity, including both canopy and understory trees. RS-derived canopy data is compared with full species data from FM using Hill numbers. The results were compared using three methods: the Bray-Curtis dissimilarity coefficient for abundance differences, Bland-Altman agreement analysis, and Species Rank Abundance Curves (RACs) for distribution patterns. This multi-phase methodology compares tree species diversity between RS and field data. Phase 1 creates a reliable canopy map, Phase 2 tests H1, assessing the accuracy of RS in estimating canopy species diversity in the BF, Phase 3 tests H2, evaluating the correlation between RS estimates of tree diversity (canopy and understory) and FM, with variations expected based on species compositions and forest management strategies. Together, these phases assess the effectiveness of RS in representing biodiversity across the BF.</ce:para>
                     <ce:section id="sec0035" view="all">
                        <ce:label>2.4.1</ce:label>
                        <ce:section-title id="sect0055">Investigation of canopy species diversity (H1)</ce:section-title>
                        <ce:para id="p0110" view="all">To compare canopy tree species diversity between RS data and FM (H1), we used Hill numbers to provide a comprehensive view of biodiversity. Hill numbers are particularly valuable for assessing ecological diversity, as they offer a unified framework to evaluate species richness, evenness, and dominance within communities (<ce:cross-refs id="crs0095" refid="bib15 bib64 bib79 bib78">Chao et al., 2014; Roswell et al., 2021; Zhao et al., 2022; Zemp et al., 2023</ce:cross-refs>). For both RS and FM, we used species incidence data to calculate Hill numbers of order 0 using species incidence data, where ‘incidence’ refers to whether a species was detected in a plot (presence/absence). Although Hill numbers of order 0 (species richness) can also be calculated using abundance data, we used presence/absence data to ensure consistency and comparability between RS and FM. For higher-order Hill numbers (<ce:italic>q</ce:italic>=1 and <ce:italic>q</ce:italic>=2), relative abundance data was used to assess species evenness and dominance. In the RS, both incidence and abundance data were derived from RS-based maps, where species presence and abundance data were inferred based on spectral and structural signatures and spatial distribution. In contrast, FM relied on direct field observations, where species presence and abundance were recorded based on field surveys. Here, abundance refers to the number of individuals of each species recorded within a plot, while relative abundance is calculated as the proportion of individuals of a given species relative to the total number of individuals recorded in that plot. We hypothesize that RS will yield significant insights into these diversity patterns, especially with regard to species compositions and management strategies. Hill numbers of order <ce:italic>q</ce:italic> for incidence data are defined in <ce:cross-ref id="cr0120" refid="eqn0005">Eq. 1</ce:cross-ref>. Specifically, when <ce:italic>q</ce:italic>= 0, it represents species richness, reflecting basic biodiversity as the total number of observed species.<ce:display>
                              <ce:formula id="eqn0005">
                                 <ce:label>(1)</ce:label>
                                 <mml:math altimg="si0001.svg">
                                    <mml:mrow>
                                       <mml:mmultiscripts>
                                          <mml:mrow>
                                             <mml:mfenced open="(" close=")">
                                                <mml:mrow>
                                                   <mml:munderover>
                                                      <mml:mo>∑</mml:mo>
                                                      <mml:mrow>
                                                         <mml:mi>i</mml:mi>
                                                         <mml:mo>=</mml:mo>
                                                         <mml:mn>1</mml:mn>
                                                      </mml:mrow>
                                                      <mml:mrow>
                                                         <mml:mi>S</mml:mi>
                                                      </mml:mrow>
                                                   </mml:munderover>
                                                   <mml:mrow>
                                                      <mml:msup>
                                                         <mml:mrow>
                                                            <mml:mfenced open="[" close="]">
                                                               <mml:mrow>
                                                                  <mml:mfrac>
                                                                     <mml:mrow>
                                                                        <mml:msub>
                                                                           <mml:mrow>
                                                                              <mml:mi>π</mml:mi>
                                                                           </mml:mrow>
                                                                           <mml:mrow>
                                                                              <mml:mi>i</mml:mi>
                                                                           </mml:mrow>
                                                                        </mml:msub>
                                                                     </mml:mrow>
                                                                     <mml:mrow>
                                                                        <mml:msubsup>
                                                                           <mml:mo>∑</mml:mo>
                                                                           <mml:mrow>
                                                                              <mml:mi>j</mml:mi>
                                                                              <mml:mo>=</mml:mo>
                                                                              <mml:mn>1</mml:mn>
                                                                           </mml:mrow>
                                                                           <mml:mrow>
                                                                              <mml:mi>S</mml:mi>
                                                                           </mml:mrow>
                                                                        </mml:msubsup>
                                                                        <mml:mrow>
                                                                           <mml:msub>
                                                                              <mml:mrow>
                                                                                 <mml:mi>π</mml:mi>
                                                                              </mml:mrow>
                                                                              <mml:mrow>
                                                                                 <mml:mi>j</mml:mi>
                                                                              </mml:mrow>
                                                                           </mml:msub>
                                                                        </mml:mrow>
                                                                     </mml:mrow>
                                                                  </mml:mfrac>
                                                               </mml:mrow>
                                                            </mml:mfenced>
                                                         </mml:mrow>
                                                         <mml:mrow>
                                                            <mml:mi>q</mml:mi>
                                                         </mml:mrow>
                                                      </mml:msup>
                                                   </mml:mrow>
                                                </mml:mrow>
                                             </mml:mfenced>
                                          </mml:mrow>
                                          <mml:none/>
                                          <mml:mrow>
                                             <mml:mn>1</mml:mn>
                                             <mml:mo>/</mml:mo>
                                             <mml:mrow>
                                                <mml:mfenced open="(" close=")">
                                                   <mml:mrow>
                                                      <mml:mn>1</mml:mn>
                                                      <mml:mo linebreak="badbreak">−</mml:mo>
                                                      <mml:mi>q</mml:mi>
                                                   </mml:mrow>
                                                </mml:mfenced>
                                             </mml:mrow>
                                          </mml:mrow>
                                          <mml:mprescripts/>
                                          <mml:none/>
                                          <mml:mrow>
                                             <mml:mi>q</mml:mi>
                                          </mml:mrow>
                                       </mml:mmultiscripts>
                                       <mml:mrow>
                                          <mml:mo>∆</mml:mo>
                                          <mml:mo linebreak="goodbreak">=</mml:mo>
                                          <mml:mo>,</mml:mo>
                                          <mml:mspace width="1em"/>
                                          <mml:mi>q</mml:mi>
                                          <mml:mo>≥</mml:mo>
                                          <mml:mn>0</mml:mn>
                                          <mml:mo>,</mml:mo>
                                          <mml:mspace width="1em"/>
                                          <mml:mi>q</mml:mi>
                                          <mml:mo>≠</mml:mo>
                                          <mml:mn>1</mml:mn>
                                       </mml:mrow>
                                    </mml:mrow>
                                 </mml:math>
                              </ce:formula>
                           </ce:display>where <ce:italic>S</ce:italic> is the number of species, <ce:italic>π</ce:italic>
                           <ce:inf loc="post">
                              <ce:italic>i</ce:italic>
                           </ce:inf> represents the incidence frequency of the <ce:italic>i</ce:italic>th species for incidence-based calculations (i.e., <ce:italic>q</ce:italic>=0), or the relative abundance of the <ce:italic>i</ce:italic>th species for abundance-based calculations (i.e., <ce:italic>q</ce:italic>=1 and <ce:italic>q</ce:italic>=2). As the order increases, Hill numbers increasingly emphasize species abundance distributions. For instance, the Shannon diversity (<ce:italic>q</ce:italic>=1) based on relative abundance, considers both species richness and evenness, giving more weight to abundant species (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0125" refid="eqn0010">Eq. 2</ce:cross-ref>). This measure emphasizes the distribution of species abundances, offering a comprehensive view of community structure.<ce:display>
                              <ce:formula id="eqn0010">
                                 <ce:label>(2)</ce:label>
                                 <mml:math altimg="si0002.svg">
                                    <mml:mmultiscripts>
                                       <mml:mrow>
                                          <mml:mo>∆</mml:mo>
                                          <mml:mo linebreak="goodbreak">=</mml:mo>
                                          <mml:munder>
                                             <mml:mrow>
                                                <mml:mi>lim</mml:mi>
                                             </mml:mrow>
                                             <mml:mrow>
                                                <mml:mi>q</mml:mi>
                                                <mml:mo>→</mml:mo>
                                                <mml:mn>1</mml:mn>
                                             </mml:mrow>
                                          </mml:munder>
                                          <mml:mrow>
                                             <mml:mrow>
                                                <mml:mspace width="1em"/>
                                             </mml:mrow>
                                             <mml:mrow>
                                                <mml:mi>q</mml:mi>
                                             </mml:mrow>
                                             <mml:mrow>
                                                <mml:mo>∆</mml:mo>
                                                <mml:mo linebreak="goodbreak">=</mml:mo>
                                                <mml:mi>exp</mml:mi>
                                                <mml:mrow>
                                                   <mml:mfenced open="(" close=")">
                                                      <mml:mrow>
                                                         <mml:mo linebreak="badbreak">−</mml:mo>
                                                         <mml:munderover>
                                                            <mml:mo>∑</mml:mo>
                                                            <mml:mrow>
                                                               <mml:mi>i</mml:mi>
                                                               <mml:mo>=</mml:mo>
                                                               <mml:mn>1</mml:mn>
                                                            </mml:mrow>
                                                            <mml:mrow>
                                                               <mml:mi>S</mml:mi>
                                                            </mml:mrow>
                                                         </mml:munderover>
                                                         <mml:mrow>
                                                            <mml:mfrac>
                                                               <mml:mrow>
                                                                  <mml:msub>
                                                                     <mml:mrow>
                                                                        <mml:mi>π</mml:mi>
                                                                     </mml:mrow>
                                                                     <mml:mrow>
                                                                        <mml:mi>i</mml:mi>
                                                                     </mml:mrow>
                                                                  </mml:msub>
                                                               </mml:mrow>
                                                               <mml:mrow>
                                                                  <mml:msubsup>
                                                                     <mml:mo>∑</mml:mo>
                                                                     <mml:mrow>
                                                                        <mml:mi>j</mml:mi>
                                                                        <mml:mo>=</mml:mo>
                                                                        <mml:mn>1</mml:mn>
                                                                     </mml:mrow>
                                                                     <mml:mrow>
                                                                        <mml:mi>S</mml:mi>
                                                                     </mml:mrow>
                                                                  </mml:msubsup>
                                                                  <mml:mrow>
                                                                     <mml:msub>
                                                                        <mml:mrow>
                                                                           <mml:mi>π</mml:mi>
                                                                        </mml:mrow>
                                                                        <mml:mrow>
                                                                           <mml:mi>j</mml:mi>
                                                                        </mml:mrow>
                                                                     </mml:msub>
                                                                  </mml:mrow>
                                                               </mml:mrow>
                                                            </mml:mfrac>
                                                            <mml:mi>log</mml:mi>
                                                            <mml:mfrac>
                                                               <mml:mrow>
                                                                  <mml:msub>
                                                                     <mml:mrow>
                                                                        <mml:mi>π</mml:mi>
                                                                     </mml:mrow>
                                                                     <mml:mrow>
                                                                        <mml:mi>i</mml:mi>
                                                                     </mml:mrow>
                                                                  </mml:msub>
                                                               </mml:mrow>
                                                               <mml:mrow>
                                                                  <mml:msubsup>
                                                                     <mml:mo>∑</mml:mo>
                                                                     <mml:mrow>
                                                                        <mml:mi>j</mml:mi>
                                                                        <mml:mo>=</mml:mo>
                                                                        <mml:mn>1</mml:mn>
                                                                     </mml:mrow>
                                                                     <mml:mrow>
                                                                        <mml:mi>S</mml:mi>
                                                                     </mml:mrow>
                                                                  </mml:msubsup>
                                                                  <mml:mrow>
                                                                     <mml:msub>
                                                                        <mml:mrow>
                                                                           <mml:mi>π</mml:mi>
                                                                        </mml:mrow>
                                                                        <mml:mrow>
                                                                           <mml:mi>j</mml:mi>
                                                                        </mml:mrow>
                                                                     </mml:msub>
                                                                  </mml:mrow>
                                                               </mml:mrow>
                                                            </mml:mfrac>
                                                         </mml:mrow>
                                                      </mml:mrow>
                                                   </mml:mfenced>
                                                </mml:mrow>
                                             </mml:mrow>
                                          </mml:mrow>
                                       </mml:mrow>
                                       <mml:none/>
                                       <mml:none/>
                                       <mml:mprescripts/>
                                       <mml:none/>
                                       <mml:mrow>
                                          <mml:mn>1</mml:mn>
                                       </mml:mrow>
                                    </mml:mmultiscripts>
                                 </mml:math>
                              </ce:formula>
                           </ce:display>
                        </ce:para>
                        <ce:para id="p0115" view="all">The next order, the Simpson or dominance-weighted diversity (<ce:italic>q</ce:italic>=2), i.e., the inverse Simpson concentration based on relative incidences (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0130" refid="eqn0015">Eq. 3</ce:cross-ref>), highlights the dominance of species and reflects the probability that two randomly selected individuals belong to the same species. This measure highlights the importance of common species within the community. A high Simpson diversity value indicates that no single species overwhelmingly dominates, while a low value suggests a community with a few dominant species (<ce:cross-refs id="crs0100" refid="bib15 bib40 bib1">Chao et al., 2014; Hsieh et al., 2016; Arasa-Gisbert et al., 2021</ce:cross-refs>).<ce:display>
                              <ce:formula id="eqn0015">
                                 <ce:label>(3)</ce:label>
                                 <mml:math altimg="si0003.svg">
                                    <mml:mmultiscripts>
                                       <mml:mrow>
                                          <mml:mo>∆</mml:mo>
                                          <mml:mo linebreak="goodbreak">=</mml:mo>
                                          <mml:mn>1</mml:mn>
                                          <mml:mo>/</mml:mo>
                                          <mml:mrow>
                                             <mml:munderover>
                                                <mml:mo>∑</mml:mo>
                                                <mml:mrow>
                                                   <mml:mi>i</mml:mi>
                                                   <mml:mo>=</mml:mo>
                                                   <mml:mn>1</mml:mn>
                                                </mml:mrow>
                                                <mml:mrow>
                                                   <mml:mi>S</mml:mi>
                                                </mml:mrow>
                                             </mml:munderover>
                                             <mml:mrow>
                                                <mml:msup>
                                                   <mml:mrow>
                                                      <mml:mfenced open="(" close=")">
                                                         <mml:mrow>
                                                            <mml:mfrac>
                                                               <mml:mrow>
                                                                  <mml:msub>
                                                                     <mml:mrow>
                                                                        <mml:mi>π</mml:mi>
                                                                     </mml:mrow>
                                                                     <mml:mrow>
                                                                        <mml:mi>i</mml:mi>
                                                                     </mml:mrow>
                                                                  </mml:msub>
                                                               </mml:mrow>
                                                               <mml:mrow>
                                                                  <mml:msubsup>
                                                                     <mml:mo>∑</mml:mo>
                                                                     <mml:mrow>
                                                                        <mml:mi>j</mml:mi>
                                                                        <mml:mo>=</mml:mo>
                                                                        <mml:mn>1</mml:mn>
                                                                     </mml:mrow>
                                                                     <mml:mrow>
                                                                        <mml:mi>S</mml:mi>
                                                                     </mml:mrow>
                                                                  </mml:msubsup>
                                                                  <mml:mrow>
                                                                     <mml:msub>
                                                                        <mml:mrow>
                                                                           <mml:mi>π</mml:mi>
                                                                        </mml:mrow>
                                                                        <mml:mrow>
                                                                           <mml:mi>j</mml:mi>
                                                                        </mml:mrow>
                                                                     </mml:msub>
                                                                  </mml:mrow>
                                                               </mml:mrow>
                                                            </mml:mfrac>
                                                         </mml:mrow>
                                                      </mml:mfenced>
                                                   </mml:mrow>
                                                   <mml:mrow>
                                                      <mml:mn>2</mml:mn>
                                                   </mml:mrow>
                                                </mml:msup>
                                             </mml:mrow>
                                          </mml:mrow>
                                       </mml:mrow>
                                       <mml:none/>
                                       <mml:none/>
                                       <mml:mprescripts/>
                                       <mml:none/>
                                       <mml:mrow>
                                          <mml:mn>2</mml:mn>
                                       </mml:mrow>
                                    </mml:mmultiscripts>
                                 </mml:math>
                              </ce:formula>
                           </ce:display>
                        </ce:para>
                        <ce:para id="p0120" view="all">By employing Hill numbers in this study, we are able to capture a gradient of diversity dimensions, from simple species presence to complex abundance relationships, which enhances our ability to identify meaningful patterns across species compositions and management categories. As an accumulation of diversity measures across plots, Hill numbers provide a unified and integrative metric that reflects broader community-level trends. Their flexibility under varying sampling efforts also enables more accurate comparisons between datasets derived from RS and FM. This methodological focus enhances our ability to uncover meaningful patterns in biodiversity and evaluates the effectiveness of RS in assessing species diversity at the plot level, ultimately supporting our hypothesis regarding its significant contributions across various forest species compositions and management categories.</ce:para>
                        <ce:para id="p0125" view="all">To evaluate the accuracy and consistency of RS in assessing biodiversity of canopy trees compared with FM, we employed three complementary methods: Correlation analysis, Bland-Altman agreement, and Bray-Curtis dissimilarity coefficient. Each method plays a unique role in this comprehensive evaluation. Correlation analysis measures the strength and direction of the linear relationship between species diversity derived from RS and FM. This analysis is particularly useful for identifying whether the diversity indices (such as Hill numbers) obtained from RS consistently increase or decrease synchronously with those from FM at the plot level. A strong correlation suggests that the RS data can reliably reflect the trends observed in FM. Bland-Altman analysis (also known as agreement analysis) further evaluates the agreement between two methods by plotting the differences between RS and FM against their averages. This approach identifies systematic biases, such as whether RS consistently overestimates (negative bias) or underestimates (positive bias) species diversity at the plot level, and quantifies the extent of random errors. The Limits of Agreement (LoA), representing the 95 % confidence interval for the differences, are calculated as the mean difference ± 1.96 times the standard deviation. These limits help determine whether the two methods agree. The Bland-Altman agreement analysis provides a direct comparison of the two methods on a plot-by-plot basis, revealing discrepancies across the range of values. This is crucial because FM and RS can exhibit high overall similarity in Hill numbers while still showing significant biases or systematic errors at the plot level. Consequently, Bland-Altman analysis offers a clearer and more comprehensive evaluation of the reliability of RS for biodiversity estimation compared with ground-truth FM data. The Bray-Curtis dissimilarity coefficient considers both species presence/absence and abundance, allowing for a more comprehensive comparison (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0135" refid="eqn0020">Eq. 4</ce:cross-ref>) (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0140" refid="bib60">Ricotta and Burrascano, 2009</ce:cross-ref>). This index is sensitive to variations in species abundance, providing a clearer picture of how well RS captures the richness and distribution of species relative to FM. The Bray-Curtis dissimilarity coefficient value ranges from 0 to 1, where 0 indicates greater similarity between the two methods and 1 indicates greater differences between the methods. This coefficient is particularly useful for understanding how well RS captures not just species presence but also their relative abundance.<ce:display>
                              <ce:formula id="eqn0020">
                                 <ce:label>(4)</ce:label>
                                 <mml:math altimg="si0004.svg">
                                    <mml:mrow>
                                       <mml:mi mathvariant="normal">BC</mml:mi>
                                       <mml:mo linebreak="goodbreak">=</mml:mo>
                                       <mml:mspace width="1em"/>
                                       <mml:mfrac>
                                          <mml:mrow>
                                             <mml:msubsup>
                                                <mml:mo>∑</mml:mo>
                                                <mml:mrow>
                                                   <mml:mi>i</mml:mi>
                                                   <mml:mo>=</mml:mo>
                                                   <mml:mn>1</mml:mn>
                                                </mml:mrow>
                                                <mml:mrow>
                                                   <mml:mi>S</mml:mi>
                                                </mml:mrow>
                                             </mml:msubsup>
                                             <mml:mrow>
                                                <mml:mfenced open="|" close="|">
                                                   <mml:mrow>
                                                      <mml:msub>
                                                         <mml:mrow>
                                                            <mml:mi>x</mml:mi>
                                                         </mml:mrow>
                                                         <mml:mrow>
                                                            <mml:mi>i</mml:mi>
                                                         </mml:mrow>
                                                      </mml:msub>
                                                      <mml:mo>−</mml:mo>
                                                      <mml:msub>
                                                         <mml:mrow>
                                                            <mml:mi>y</mml:mi>
                                                         </mml:mrow>
                                                         <mml:mrow>
                                                            <mml:mi>i</mml:mi>
                                                         </mml:mrow>
                                                      </mml:msub>
                                                   </mml:mrow>
                                                </mml:mfenced>
                                             </mml:mrow>
                                          </mml:mrow>
                                          <mml:mrow>
                                             <mml:msubsup>
                                                <mml:mo>∑</mml:mo>
                                                <mml:mrow>
                                                   <mml:mi>i</mml:mi>
                                                   <mml:mo>=</mml:mo>
                                                   <mml:mn>1</mml:mn>
                                                </mml:mrow>
                                                <mml:mrow>
                                                   <mml:mi>S</mml:mi>
                                                </mml:mrow>
                                             </mml:msubsup>
                                             <mml:mrow>
                                                <mml:mfenced open="(" close=")">
                                                   <mml:mrow>
                                                      <mml:msub>
                                                         <mml:mrow>
                                                            <mml:mi>x</mml:mi>
                                                         </mml:mrow>
                                                         <mml:mrow>
                                                            <mml:mi>i</mml:mi>
                                                         </mml:mrow>
                                                      </mml:msub>
                                                      <mml:mo>+</mml:mo>
                                                      <mml:msub>
                                                         <mml:mrow>
                                                            <mml:mi>y</mml:mi>
                                                         </mml:mrow>
                                                         <mml:mrow>
                                                            <mml:mi>i</mml:mi>
                                                         </mml:mrow>
                                                      </mml:msub>
                                                   </mml:mrow>
                                                </mml:mfenced>
                                             </mml:mrow>
                                          </mml:mrow>
                                       </mml:mfrac>
                                    </mml:mrow>
                                 </mml:math>
                              </ce:formula>
                           </ce:display>where BC is the Bray-Curtis dissimilarity coefficient, <ce:italic>x</ce:italic>
                           <ce:inf loc="post">
                              <ce:italic>i</ce:italic>
                           </ce:inf> and <ce:italic>y</ce:italic>
                           <ce:inf loc="post">
                              <ce:italic>i</ce:italic>
                           </ce:inf> represent the relative abundance of species <ce:italic>i</ce:italic> in the FM and RS, respectively, <ce:italic>S</ce:italic> is the total number of species.</ce:para>
                     </ce:section>
                     <ce:section id="sec0040" view="all">
                        <ce:label>2.4.2</ce:label>
                        <ce:section-title id="sect0060">Investigation of All species diversity (H2)</ce:section-title>
                        <ce:para id="p0130" view="all">Since FM captures all trees, including both canopy and understory species individuals, whereas RS typically detects only canopy trees, this difference in detection can influence the accuracy and completeness of species diversity assessments when relying on RS data alone. The contribution of understory species to overall biodiversity is likely to affect species richness and diversity measurements, leading to differences between RS and FM-based metrics. To evaluate the effectiveness of RS in estimating species diversity, we will compare tree species diversity from RS and FM using Hill numbers across a range of various species compositions and forest management strategies. Hill numbers provide a powerful framework for these comparisons by allowing us to assess species richness, evenness, and dominance.</ce:para>
                        <ce:para id="p0135" view="all">By applying different orders of Hill numbers, we assess biodiversity across a gradient from species richness to dominance-weighted diversity. As noted by <ce:cross-ref id="cr0145" refid="bib15">Chao et al. (2014)</ce:cross-ref>, Hill numbers allow for both interpolation (within the range of observed sample sizes) and extrapolation (beyond the observed sample size), estimating how diversity might increase with additional sampling. Extrapolation works by modeling the rate at which new species are likely to be encountered, based on the observed species abundance distribution. This method provides a more complete picture of potential diversity and helps evaluate the reliability of RS in reflecting biodiversity across varying species compositions and management strategies. By comparing observed and extrapolated diversity within both RS and FM datasets, we gain deeper insight into the completeness of each method and the consistency of diversity estimates between them, supporting our hypothesis that RS can serve as a reliable proxy for biodiversity across varying forest types.</ce:para>
                        <ce:para id="p0140" view="all">To assess the accuracy of RS in estimating tree species diversity compared with FM, we employed three complementary methods: Bray-Curtis dissimilarity coefficient, Bland-Altman agreement analysis, and RACs. In addition to the first two methods, we will compare RACs to evaluate whether RS reflects similar insights into tree species diversity. RACs display the relative abundance of species, ranked from most to least abundant, thereby illustrating species diversity and evenness. The RACs derived from FM serve as the ground truth, while those generated from RS reflect how well species are identified through this technology.</ce:para>
                     </ce:section>
                  </ce:section>
               </ce:section>
               <ce:section id="sec0045" role="results" view="all">
                  <ce:label>3</ce:label>
                  <ce:section-title id="sect0065">Results</ce:section-title>
                  <ce:section id="sec0050" view="all">
                     <ce:label>3.1</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="sect0070">Field observations of species diversity</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="p0145" view="all">The study area contained 20 tree species, classified into 14 species groups due to species similarity and RS dataset limitations in discriminating within the same genus. These species groups included spruce <ce:italic>Picea abies</ce:italic> (L.) H. KARST.; hornbeam <ce:italic>Carpinus betulus</ce:italic> L.; pine <ce:italic>Pinus sylvestris</ce:italic> L.; birch <ce:italic>Betula pendula</ce:italic> ROTH &amp; <ce:italic>B. pubescens</ce:italic> EHRH.; oak <ce:italic>Quercus robur</ce:italic> L.; alder <ce:italic>Alnus glutinosa</ce:italic> (L.) GAERTN.; lime <ce:italic>Tilia cordata</ce:italic> MILL.; aspen <ce:italic>Populus tremula</ce:italic> L.; maple <ce:italic>Acer platanoides</ce:italic> L.; ash <ce:italic>Fraxinus excelsior</ce:italic> L.; elm <ce:italic>Ulmus glabra</ce:italic> HUDS., <ce:italic>U. minor</ce:italic> MILL. &amp; <ce:italic>U. laevis</ce:italic> PALL.; willow <ce:italic>Salix cinerea</ce:italic> L., <ce:italic>S. caprea</ce:italic> L., <ce:italic>S. aurita</ce:italic> L. &amp; <ce:italic>S. fragilis</ce:italic> L.; rowan <ce:italic>Sorbus aucuparia</ce:italic> (L.) em. HEDL.; and common pear <ce:italic>Pyrus pyraster</ce:italic> (L.) BURGSD. (Fig. A.1).</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0150" view="all">Canopy densities were generally higher than understory densities across species compositions (BS, CS, MS) and management categories (SR, NR, MF). The relationship between canopy and understory tree diversity was weak, as indicated by low R² values for most diversity metrics (<ce:italic>q</ce:italic>=0, 1, 2). In species compositions, BS showed stable canopy densities, with more variation in the understory. PERMANOVA revealed significant, but smaller, differences in species presence/absence (F = 13.46, <ce:italic>p</ce:italic>-value = 0.001), while correlations remained weak. In CS, pine dominated the canopy, and hornbeam increased in the understory. PERMANOVA confirmed significant species differences (F = 35.20, <ce:italic>p</ce:italic>-value = 0.001), but weak correlation (e.g., R² = 0.01 for <ce:italic>q</ce:italic>=2). MS showed a more balanced species distribution, though some species declined in the understory, with weak correlations. Among management categories, SR had the lowest species richness, with hornbeam dominating both layers. PERMANOVA showed no significant differences (F = 1.47, <ce:italic>p</ce:italic>-value &gt; 0.1), and weak correlations, especially with <ce:italic>q</ce:italic>= 2. In NR, alder was abundant in the canopy, while spruce and hornbeam regenerated strongly in the understory. PERMANOVA showed significant spatial differences (F = 9.16, <ce:italic>p</ce:italic>-value = 0.001), but moderate, weak correlations. Finally, in MF, the highest species diversity was recorded, with all 14 species present in both layers and the highest canopy density. PERMANOVA revealed strong spatial differences (F = 26.25, <ce:italic>p</ce:italic>-value = 0.001), with moderate but weak correlations. These results suggest that shifts in species composition and diversity are influenced by forest type and management strategy (Fig. A.1-A.4).</ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
                  <ce:section id="sec0055" view="all">
                     <ce:label>3.2</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="sect0075">Remote sensing-based species identification</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="p0155" view="all">The XGBoost model, using combined ALS and CIR data, shows varying species identification performance (Fig. A.4 and A.5), which can be attributed to differences in spectral (Fig. A.6), intensity, and structural features of species (Fig. A.7). Species like spruce and pine achieve high F1 (0.92) and AUC values (0.994, 0.996), indicating strong classification accuracy. Moderately performing species, such as oak, have lower F1 (0.77) and AUC (0.976), while species like lime and maple show high AUC (0.967) but lower F1 (0.68, 0.59). Lower-performing species like birch, aspen, and hornbeam have F1 between 0.55 and 0.60, with adequate differentiation but challenges balancing precision and recall. Ash performs the weakest with an F1 of 0.21 and AUC of 0.788. RS shows trends of accurately identifying frequent species, like spruce and pine, while struggling with low-frequency species. The comparison of species frequencies observed in FM and identified by RS highlights the strength of RS in detecting frequent species, as well as its limitations in identifying low-frequency ones (Fig. A.8). It is important to note that during the preparation of species maps, we classified 10 species and four additional classes; i.e., “other broadleaved species” (including elm, willow, rowan, and common pear), which were not reliably detected by the RS datasets and our methodology, as well as “dead broadleaved species,” “dead spruce,” and “dead pine” (Fig. A.5). The four classes were excluded, and only the map of the 10 identified species was used for the species diversity assessment.</ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
                  <ce:section id="sec0060" view="all">
                     <ce:label>3.3</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="sect0080">Remote sensing of canopy species diversity (H1)</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="p0160" view="all">Based on the Hill numbers for canopy trees from FM and RS (<ce:float-anchor refid="fig0015"/>
                        <ce:cross-ref id="cr0150" refid="fig0015">Fig. 3</ce:cross-ref>), species compositions and management categories show distinct patterns. In the BS, high R² values across all metrics indicate a strong RS-FM correlation, effectively representing both rare and common species at the plot level. In contrast, CS has moderate R² values, indicating a balanced representation of species by RS with a slight emphasis on evenness and species dominance. MS displays lower R² values, suggesting moderate RS reliability for diversity assessment. Among management categories, SR shows the highest R² values across all metrics, indicating RS effectively captures over 80 percent of diversity dynamics with strong FM correlation and a balanced representation of species richness and evenness. In contrast, NR has slightly lower R² values compared with SR, suggesting moderate efficiency of RS with a less even representation among species. MF shows similar R² values to NR, indicating a balanced RS efficiency but with slight variations in the representation of different species.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0165" view="all">
                        <ce:float-anchor refid="fig0020"/>
                        <ce:cross-ref id="cr0155" refid="fig0020">Fig. 4</ce:cross-ref> (left panel) compares canopy tree diversity using Hill numbers derived from FM (orange lines) and RS (blue lines) across different species compositions and management categories. In BS, RS significantly underestimates species richness (<ce:italic>q</ce:italic>=0; FM: 12, RS: 10), based on individual counts of 1185 (FM) and 944 (RS), while significantly overestimating diversity at <ce:italic>q</ce:italic>= 1 and <ce:italic>q</ce:italic>= 2. In CS, RS also underestimates <ce:italic>q</ce:italic>= 0, though not significantly (FM: 12, RS: 10), with individual counts of 1738 (FM) and 1242 (RS). For Shannon (<ce:italic>q</ce:italic>=1; FM: 3.18, RS: 3.65) and Simpson (<ce:italic>q</ce:italic>=2) indices, RS estimates are higher than FM, but only <ce:italic>q</ce:italic>= 1 shows a significant difference. In MS, RS estimates moderately align with FM, with a significant overestimation at <ce:italic>q</ce:italic>= 1 (FM: 7.00, RS: 7.52) and a smaller, non-significant overestimation at <ce:italic>q</ce:italic>= 2 (FM: 6.25, RS: 6.60). Overall, RS tends to underestimate species richness in all species compositions while consistently overestimating diversity at higher orders (<ce:italic>q</ce:italic>=1 and 2), particularly in BS.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0170" view="all">In terms of management categories, in SR, RS closely matches FM for species richness (<ce:italic>q</ce:italic>=0; FM: 9, RS: 9), based on individual counts of 202 (FM) and 148 (RS). However, wider confidence intervals reflect greater variability, and RS significantly overestimates both <ce:italic>q</ce:italic>= 1 (FM: 5.20, RS: 6.63) and <ce:italic>q</ce:italic>= 2. In NR, RS reasonably aligns with FM at <ce:italic>q</ce:italic>= 0 (FM: 10; RS: 10), while significantly overestimating <ce:italic>q</ce:italic>= 1 (FM: 6.44, RS: 6.96). In MF, RS significantly underestimates species richness (<ce:italic>q</ce:italic>=0; FM: 14, RS: 10), with individual counts of 2784 (FM) and 2121 (RS). For <ce:italic>q</ce:italic>= 1 (FM: 6.27, RS: 6.51) and <ce:italic>q</ce:italic>= 2, RS slightly overestimates the indices, though the differences are not significant. Across management categories, RS tends to underestimate species richness in MF while overestimating evenness and dominance, with the largest discrepancies observed in strictly protected (i.e., SR) forests.</ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
                  <ce:section id="sec0065" view="all">
                     <ce:label>3.4</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="sect0085">Remote sensing of all species diversity (H2)</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="p0175" view="all">The right panel in <ce:cross-ref id="cr0160" refid="fig0020">Fig. 4</ce:cross-ref> shows that in BS, RS and FM estimates align well for Shannon (<ce:italic>q</ce:italic>=1; FM: 5.59, RS: 5.89) and Simpson (<ce:italic>q</ce:italic>=2; FM: 4.12, RS: 4.22) indices, with non-significant slight overestimations, based on individual counts of 2007 (FM) and 944 (RS). However, RS significantly underestimates species richness (<ce:italic>q</ce:italic>=0; FM: 12, RS: 10), suggesting that RS may miss some less abundant species in more compositionally diverse stands. In CS, RS consistently but non-significantly underestimates richness (<ce:italic>q</ce:italic>=0; FM: 12, RS: 10) for 2658 (FM) and 1242 (RS) individuals, while showing a non-significant overestimation for <ce:italic>q</ce:italic>= 1 (FM: 3.55, RS: 3.65) and underestimation for <ce:italic>q</ce:italic>= 2, highlighting that RS struggles to consistently capture the full range of diversity in more homogeneous canopies. In MS, RS significantly underestimates species richness (<ce:italic>q</ce:italic>=0; FM: 12, RS: 10) based on 1887 (FM) and 795 (RS) individuals, while significantly overestimating both Shannon (<ce:italic>q</ce:italic>=1; FM: 6.08, RS: 7.52) and Simpson (<ce:italic>q</ce:italic>=2) indices. The increased structural and compositional complexity in MS may lead to an overrepresentation of dominant species in RS outputs. Overall, across species compositions, RS tends to underestimate species richness while moderately to significantly overestimating evenness and dominance, particularly in structurally complex stands (i.e., MS).</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0180" view="all">Regarding management categories, in SR, RS slightly underestimates richness (<ce:italic>q</ce:italic>=0; FM: 10, RS: 9) based on individual counts of 342 (FM) and 148 (RS), though not significantly. However, RS significantly overestimates diversity at higher orders (e.g., <ce:italic>q</ce:italic>=1; FM: 4.78, RS: 6.63), with wider confidence intervals indicating high variability. This suggests that RS may overestimate diversity under low-disturbance conditions. In NR, RS estimates significantly overestimate <ce:italic>q</ce:italic>= 1 (FM: 6.03, RS: 6.96) and <ce:italic>q</ce:italic>= 2, while the difference in richness (<ce:italic>q</ce:italic>=0; FM: 12, RS: 10) is not significant. In MF, RS significantly underestimates species richness (<ce:italic>q</ce:italic>=0; FM: 14, RS: 10), based on 4454 (FM) and 2121 (RS) individuals, but shows only slight, non-significant overestimations for <ce:italic>q</ce:italic>= 1 (FM: 6.26, RS: 6.51) and <ce:italic>q</ce:italic>= 2, suggesting RS may better reflect evenness than richness under management. In general, across management categories, RS tends to underestimate richness and overestimate evenness, with the greatest discrepancies observed in undisturbed forests (i.e., SR).</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0185" view="all">The dashed lines in the Hill number plots (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0165" refid="fig0020">Fig. 4</ce:cross-ref>) represent extrapolated estimates of diversity for each index (<ce:italic>q</ce:italic>= 0, 1, and 2), based on twice the observed data. These extrapolations predict diversity values for an increased sample size, effectively doubling the number of individuals compared to the observed counts. Extrapolation led to an increase in richness (<ce:italic>q</ce:italic>=0) in CS for both canopy and all trees, as well as in SR for all trees, indicating that the observed richness may be underrepresented at the current sample size. However, for the remaining diversity orders (<ce:italic>q</ce:italic>=1 and 2) and across all other categories, the extrapolated values did not show an increase in the indices. This suggests that for these indices, the observed data may already capture most of the diversity information, and further sampling would have a minimal effect on the overall diversity estimates.</ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
                  <ce:section id="sec0070" view="all">
                     <ce:label>3.5</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="sect0090">Accuracy assessment</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="p0190" view="all">The comparison of RS and FM for canopy tree diversity across species compositions and management categories (H1) reveals consistent patterns in both Bland-Altman agreement (<ce:float-anchor refid="fig0025"/>
                        <ce:cross-ref id="cr0170" refid="fig0025">Fig. 5</ce:cross-ref>, upper panel) and Bray-Curtis dissimilarity (Fig. A.9, left panel). For species compositions, BS shows the best agreement, with Bland-Altman bias decreasing from −0.32 (<ce:italic>q</ce:italic>=0) to −0.07 (<ce:italic>q</ce:italic>=2), and Bray-Curtis coefficients slightly reducing across <ce:italic>q</ce:italic> values, indicating overestimation of species at the plot level. In CS, RS overestimates species richness (bias = −0.16 at <ce:italic>q</ce:italic>=0), but agreement improves at <ce:italic>q</ce:italic>= 2 (-0.01), mirroring an increase in Bray-Curtis dissimilarity, suggesting weaker identification of dominant species. MS exhibits greater RS overestimation at <ce:italic>q</ce:italic>= 0 (-0.41), with bias reducing to −0.06 at <ce:italic>q</ce:italic>= 2. Bray-Curtis values remain moderate and stable, reflecting consistent but less precise diversity estimation. Among management categories, SR shows the highest overestimation at <ce:italic>q</ce:italic>= 0 (Bland-Altman bias = −0.76), but agreement improves at <ce:italic>q</ce:italic>= 2 (-0.17), likely due to minimal disturbance. NR exhibits moderate bias (-0.31 at <ce:italic>q</ce:italic>=0, −0.03 at <ce:italic>q</ce:italic>=2) and stable Bray-Curtis values, suggesting balanced but less precise species identification. MF shows the best overall performance in Bland-Altman (bias decreasing from −0.27 to −0.03), indicating slight improvement for dominant species and overall alignment with FM. For canopy trees, RS generally overestimates species richness at the plot level, especially in SR and MS, but agreement improves for dominant species, with the best alignment in CS and MF and weaker performance in BS and NR.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0195" view="all">The comparison of RS and FM for all tree diversity (H2) (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0175" refid="fig0025">Fig. 5</ce:cross-ref>, lower panel) reveals varying performance across species compositions and management categories. For species compositions, MS showed the best agreement between RS and FM, with Bland-Altman bias decreasing from 0.17 (<ce:italic>q</ce:italic>=0) to near zero at <ce:italic>q</ce:italic>= 2, and Bray-Curtis coefficients similarly decreasing across <ce:italic>q</ce:italic> values (Fig. A.9, right panel), indicating strong alignment, especially for dominant species. BS and CS exhibited weaker agreement, with bias reducing from 0.35 (<ce:italic>q</ce:italic>=0) to near zero (<ce:italic>q</ce:italic>=2), while Bray-Curtis coefficients remained higher, suggesting moderate representation of species richness but weaker identification of dominant species. Among management categories, MF showed the strongest agreement, with a bias of 0.32 at <ce:italic>q</ce:italic>= 0 that improved at higher <ce:italic>q</ce:italic> values, with a moderate Bray-Curtis coefficients, indicating a better match for dominant species. NR performed weak, with bias decreasing from 0.40 (<ce:italic>q</ce:italic>=0) to −0.03 (<ce:italic>q</ce:italic>=2), while Bray-Curtis coefficients remained stable (0.4484–0.4250), reflecting consistent but moderate agreement. SR also exhibited weak agreements, with moderate Bray-Curtis coefficients and biases reducing from −0.35 (<ce:italic>q</ce:italic>=0) to −0.19 (<ce:italic>q</ce:italic>=2), showing slight improvement but still weaker alignment overall. These results suggest that RS tends to underestimate diversity of all trees in all categories, while overestimating it in SR at the plot level, but agreement improves at higher diversity orders, particularly in MS and MF.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0200" view="all">The comparison between FM and RS highlights how RS captures species abundance differently, with log scale values revealing the rank order of species within various species compositions (<ce:float-anchor refid="fig0030"/>
                        <ce:cross-ref id="cr0180" refid="fig0030">Fig. 6</ce:cross-ref>) (H2). Across BS, CS, and MS, RS often follows similar patterns to FM but shows notable variations in specific cases. In all three species compositions, species like spruce and hornbeam consistently exhibit slightly lower log values in RS compared with FM, suggesting that RS may underestimate the abundance of these species due to methodological limitations. Conversely, species such as pine in BS (1.505 vs. 0.602) and ash in CS (0.845 vs. 0) and MS (1.380 vs. 0.845) demonstrate significantly higher ranks in RS, which may result from differences in species visibility, distribution patterns, or misclassification by RS.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0205" view="all">The comparison of FM and RS across different management categories highlights consistent trends in how RS captures species abundance. In all categories, species such as spruce and hornbeam generally show lower log values in RS compared with FM, indicating that RS may underestimate their abundance. This pattern is evident in SR (e.g., spruce: 1.755 vs. 2.146), NR (spruce: 2.250 vs. 2.895), and MF (spruce: 2.760 vs. 3.278). Conversely, ash consistently demonstrates a higher rank in RS compared with FM across all categories. For example, in SR, the log value of ash in RS (1.041) exceeds FM (0.301), while in NR and MF, similar patterns are observed (e.g., 1.230 vs. 1.041 in NR; 1.398 vs. 1.230 in MF). These discrepancies likely stem from misclassification or inherent limitations in the identification capabilities of RS, particularly when it comes to less abundant species. This is evident from the zeros in the RS data for elm, willow, rowan, and common pear, classified as “other broadleaved species” (Table A.3, Fig. A.5), across all stands, highlighting the challenges RS faces in identifying less abundant species.</ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
               </ce:section>
               <ce:section id="sec0075" role="discussion" view="all">
                  <ce:label>4</ce:label>
                  <ce:section-title id="sect0095">Discussion</ce:section-title>
                  <ce:section id="sec0080" view="all">
                     <ce:label>4.1</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="sect0100">Insights from the field measurements</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="p0210" view="all">The differences in species densities between canopy and understory layers highlight complex interactions between forest species compositions and management strategies in the BF. Significant trends, such as the dominance of competitive species in some parts (e.g., hornbeam in BS and SR), variations in understory, and shifts in species presence, underscore the substantial impacts of different species compositions and management strategies. In line with our findings (Fig. A.1-A.3), <ce:cross-ref id="cr0185" refid="bib13">Cavard et al. (2011)</ce:cross-ref> highlighted that in MS, the composition of understory species is not strongly correlated with canopy composition, suggesting that MS can support a diverse understory. However, there is little evidence of understory species uniquely associated with MS, such as the absence of willow and common pear in the canopy but their presence in the understory of MS. Additionally, <ce:cross-ref id="cr0190" refid="bib9">Bohlman (2015)</ce:cross-ref> showed that the relationship between understory and canopy species composition is complex; the canopy supports a diverse range of species, many of which are not found in the understory in BS in an OGF. For example, pine is present in the canopy but absent from the understory in BS (in the BF). In SR, the canopy significantly impacts understory composition, as reflected by the closer alignment between canopy and understory densities, indicating stronger interactions compared with the more independent dynamics observed in other stands (e.g., BS, NR). SR tends to favor competitive species like hornbeam (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0195" refid="bib21">Czerepko et al., 2021</ce:cross-ref>) but results in reduced diversity and a homogenized composition, which raises concerns about long-term resilience. NR promotes diverse recruitment and structural complexity, although some species present in the understory have less abundance (e.g., alder). MF achieves maximum species diversity across both layers, but trade-offs, such as declines in understory densities for certain species (e.g., aspen). These findings highlight the critical role of species composition and management strategies in shaping the relationship between canopy and understory species structure, underscoring the importance of evaluating the effectiveness of RS in stands with different species structures. Additionally, <ce:cross-ref id="cr0200" refid="bib7">Barbier et al. (2009)</ce:cross-ref> noted that, beyond canopy species diversity, structural factors such as canopy cover and tree basal area also influence understory species diversity. Long-term studies are necessary to monitor species dynamics and to explore the complex interactions between canopy and understory diversity, whether shaped by species composition or structural attributes, as well as the parameters influencing these relationships, particularly in response to changing environmental conditions and human impacts.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0215" view="all">While our analysis highlights the structural differences in species compositions and management categories, we avoid going into the details of species mixture, as this is beyond the primary aim of our study (H1, H2). Our focus is on evaluating the efficiency of RS in analyzing tree species diversity. By examining forest stands with canopy and understory structures ranging from significantly different to closely aligned (Fig. A.2), we demonstrated how species mixture influences RS efficiency, emphasizing that variations in canopy and understory dynamics can significantly impact the accuracy and reliability of RS-based assessments.</ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
                  <ce:section id="sec0085" view="all">
                     <ce:label>4.2</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="sect0105">Findings from the remote sensing maps</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="p0220" view="all">In this study, we identified 10 of the 14 species groups in the area (Fig. A.4 and A.5) by integrating structural, intensity, and spectral features from active and passive RS datasets (Table A.2, Fig. A.6 and A.7), while the remaining four species groups (i.e., elm, willow, rowan, and common pear) were classified as “other broadleaved species” (Table A.3; Fig. A.5). This method aligns with prior research (<ce:cross-refs id="crs0105" refid="bib22 bib74 bib68 bib80">Deng et al., 2016; Wu et al., 2018; Toivonen et al., 2023; Zhong et al., 2024</ce:cross-refs>) and highlights the complementary strengths of active and passive RS data. While we did not directly compare the species identification accuracy of individual RS datasets versus their combined use, our findings are supported by <ce:cross-ref id="cr0205" refid="bib65">Shi et al. (2020)</ce:cross-ref>, who demonstrated improved identification accuracy for three broadleaved and two coniferous species using a combination of LiDAR data and CIR imagery. Moreover, their results validated the reliability of this method in detecting eight broadleaved and two coniferous species in the BF. These findings underscore the effectiveness of integrating active and passive RS data for species mapping.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0225" view="all">Upon further analysis of the species not identified in each category, we found that they exhibited low canopy layer frequency (e.g., elm, willow, and common pear with 4, 14, and 6 individuals, respectively, in BS), which likely explains the challenges in their detection (Fig. A.8). Future research could investigate whether there is a strong correlation between species frequency in the canopy layer and their identification rates using RS data. This low frequency might also impact the training process of classification algorithms (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0210" refid="bib49">Liu et al., 2024</ce:cross-ref>). In such cases, pre-trained machine learning and deep learning models could provide significant advantages. For instance, <ce:cross-ref id="cr0215" refid="bib31">Fromm et al. (2019)</ce:cross-ref> demonstrated the efficacy of a pre-trained convolutional neural network (CNN) in automatically detecting conifer seedlings in drone imagery. Their method reduced the size of the training dataset required, without a notable loss in accuracy. Incorporating similar methods could help mitigate the challenges posed by species with low frequencies in the canopy layer.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0230" view="all">In this study, XGBoost was more reliable than Random Forest (RF) for species classification (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0220" refid="bib24">Erfanifard et al., 2024</ce:cross-ref>). Comparing F1 revealed that XGBoost outperformed RF for 70 % of species (e.g., spruce, hornbeam, pine, oak, alder, lime, aspen), particularly for higher-frequency species like spruce and pine. XGBoost also performed better for the two coniferous species (spruce and pine) and several broadleaved species (e.g., hornbeam). However, both algorithms struggled with low-frequency species, although XGBoost showed improvements for mid-frequency species like oak and alder. RF, however, had higher efficiency for low-frequency species such as maple and ash. This indicates that species frequency may influence the performance of classification algorithms, as also noted by <ce:cross-ref id="cr0225" refid="bib42">Immitzer and Atzberger (2023)</ce:cross-ref>. Future research could focus on integrating multiple machine learning or deep learning algorithms to enhance species identification in RS data, particularly by considering the strengths of different algorithms across various frequency ranges. Such hybrid approaches could offer more robust solutions for species classification challenges.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0235" view="all">The species identification rate in RS data plays a pivotal role in RS-based biodiversity assessments, however, RS has inherent limitations. While previous studies have demonstrated the efficiency of combining ALS and CIR imagery for species mapping (<ce:cross-refs id="crs0110" refid="bib44 bib42 bib48">Kamińska et al., 2021; Immitzer and Atzberger, 2023; Lisiewicz et al., 2025</ce:cross-refs>), one of the challenges in this study was the insufficient detail provided by the RS datasets to distinguish between species within the same genus (e.g., <ce:italic>Betula pendula, Betula pubescens</ce:italic>). Consequently, we grouped 11 species into 4 species groups, as the similarity among species within the same genus exceeded the discriminative capabilities of the available RS data. Similarly, as illustrated in Fig. A.6, the spectral reflectance curves of different species show generally small differences, with only a few exceptions. This suggests that spectral information alone may be weakly discriminative, particularly among closely related species. While structural information likely contributes to improving classification, inter-species differences in structural traits are also relatively subtle. Furthermore, we acknowledge that the classification performance might be slightly biased (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0230" refid="fig0030">Fig. 6</ce:cross-ref>) due to potential spatial autocorrelation between plots used for training and those used for validation. By comparison, studies using more advanced RS datasets have achieved greater success in distinguishing closely related species. For example, <ce:cross-ref id="cr0235" refid="bib12">Budei et al. (2018)</ce:cross-ref> utilized three-wavelength airborne LiDAR data to successfully differentiate between five species within the same coniferous genera (<ce:italic>Picea</ce:italic> spp. and <ce:italic>Pinus</ce:italic> spp.). Similarly, <ce:cross-ref id="cr0240" refid="bib41">Huang et al. (2024)</ce:cross-ref> employed a deep learning algorithm on UAV-based RGB imagery to discriminate between two <ce:italic>Pinus</ce:italic> species. These studies highlight how the capabilities of RS data significantly influence species identification success rates.</ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
                  <ce:section id="sec0090" view="all">
                     <ce:label>4.3</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="sect0110">RS reliability in assessing canopy species diversity (H1)</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="p0240" view="all">Our results demonstrate the varying efficacy of RS in assessing canopy tree diversity across species compositions and management categories, as evidenced by comparisons with FM. In BS, RS exhibits strong correlations with FM for all Hill numbers at the plot level (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0245" refid="fig0015">Fig. 3</ce:cross-ref>), indicating reliable spatial consistency in diversity detection. However, Hill number-based accumulation curves (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0250" refid="fig0020">Fig. 4</ce:cross-ref>, left panel) and Bland-Altman analysis (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0255" refid="fig0025">Fig. 5</ce:cross-ref>, upper panel) reveal systematic bias. RS underestimates species richness (<ce:italic>q</ce:italic>=0) while overestimating Shannon and Simpson diversity (<ce:italic>q</ce:italic>=1 and 2). This pattern suggests that RS effectively detects species diversity at the plot level but may overlook evenness and dominance dynamics when diversity is accumulated, potentially due to limited sensitivity to species abundances or spectral confusion. Despite this, the relatively close Bray-Curtis dissimilarity coefficients (Fig. A.9, left panel) at higher diversity orders indicate better alignment for dominant species. Persistent challenges remain in capturing less abundant species such as elm, willow, rowan, and common pear (classified as “other broadleaved species” in this study, <ce:cross-ref id="cr0260" refid="fig0030">Fig. 6</ce:cross-ref>, Table A.3), as well as in distinguishing taxonomically similar species. In CS, RS underestimates species richness (<ce:italic>q</ce:italic>=0) but overestimates Shannon and Simpson diversity (<ce:italic>q</ce:italic>=1 and 2) (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0265" refid="fig0020">Fig. 4</ce:cross-ref>, left panel), suggesting reduced sensitivity to evenness and the presence of rare species, which may lead to misclassification. Bland-Altman analysis supports this at the plot level, showing improved agreement from <ce:italic>q</ce:italic>= 0 to <ce:italic>q</ce:italic>= 2 and confirming the relative reliability of RS for detecting dominant species. Although RS performs moderately in CS, its accuracy is limited by challenges in capturing richness and evenness. A similar trend is observed in MS, where RS shows moderate reliability with better identification of dominant species, but underrepresents rare ones. However, the estimation of Hill numbers in MS is not statistically significant at either the plot or accumulated levels and RS shows relatively better performance in MS, where species distributions are more balanced and RS estimates closely match FM (Fig. A.8). In contrast, its accuracy declines in CS and especially in BS, where uneven distributions and low-frequency species are more prevalent.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0245" view="all">RS reliability also varies across management categories. In SR, RS demonstrates the highest efficiency in capturing species richness, aligning closely with FM. However, for values of <ce:italic>q</ce:italic>= 1 and 2, the confidence intervals were notably wide (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0270" refid="fig0020">Fig. 4</ce:cross-ref>, left panel), suggesting some variability in the estimates. This variability could be attributed to the sensitivity of these indices to species abundance, where RS may be less accurate in predicting the presence of these species in the plots. Furthermore, dominant species, such as hornbeam, were significantly underrepresented (Fig. A.8), therefore, the RS maps exhibited biases in estimating the densities of dominant species, which contributed to overestimated Hill numbers in the accumulation curves. This is consistent with the observed highest Bland-Altman bias at the plot level (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0275" refid="fig0025">Fig. 5</ce:cross-ref>, upper panel), indicating a systematic overestimation in RS-derived values compared to FM. In NR, RS reliably represents species such as alder and oak, but it tends to overestimate evenness and underrepresent species like hornbeam and spruce (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0280" refid="fig0030">Fig. 6</ce:cross-ref>). Despite these discrepancies, RS aligns well with FM for <ce:italic>q</ce:italic>= 0 and dominance-weighted diversity (<ce:italic>q</ce:italic>=2), and it shows reduced Bland-Altman bias for higher-order Hill numbers at the plot level. In MF, RS demonstrates balanced performance, with R² values comparable to NR (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0285" refid="fig0015">Fig. 3</ce:cross-ref>), minimal bias at <ce:italic>q</ce:italic>= 2 (-0.03, <ce:cross-ref id="cr0290" refid="fig0025">Fig. 5</ce:cross-ref>, upper panel), and consistent results for dominant species, despite weaker alignment for rare species (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0295" refid="fig0030">Fig. 6</ce:cross-ref>). Although <ce:italic>q</ce:italic>= 0 was significantly underestimated in the accumulation curves, no significant differences were observed for <ce:italic>q</ce:italic>= 1 and 2 (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0300" refid="fig0020">Fig. 4</ce:cross-ref>, left panel). These results suggest that RS effectively captures the dominant species and overall diversity patterns, but may struggle with rare species due to their smaller size or similar spectral signatures. This limitation could potentially be mitigated through synthetic over- and undersampling techniques (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0305" refid="bib69">Toivonen et al., 2024</ce:cross-ref>) or analytical approaches specifically geared toward rare species (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0310" refid="bib73">Weinstein et al., 2023</ce:cross-ref>), which may improve classification performance for underrepresented classes. Overall, RS proves highly effective in balanced, homogenous stands like MF, though its accuracy diminishes in heterogeneous or less evenly distributed contexts such as SR. Our findings align with previous research on RS-based biodiversity assessments. Studies like <ce:cross-ref id="cr0315" refid="bib28">Fassnacht et al. (2022)</ce:cross-ref> and <ce:cross-ref id="cr0320" refid="bib49">Liu et al. (2024)</ce:cross-ref> emphasize the critical role of species composition and distribution in determining RS accuracy. Similarly, <ce:cross-ref id="cr0325" refid="bib16">Chaurasia et al. (2020)</ce:cross-ref> found that diversity maps for abundant species exhibit higher accuracy, underscoring the strength of RS in mapping dominant species.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0250" view="all">Our analysis shows that RS is most reliable for canopy tree diversity, particularly in MF, as supported by both Bland-Altman analysis at the plot level and accumulated Hill numbers. Hill numbers indicate strong RS performance in MS, while Bland-Altman results highlight higher agreement in CS, reflecting the influence of structural stability and balanced species distributions in reducing heterogeneity. RS proves effective for assessing canopy tree diversity in these contexts, though it struggles to distinguish rare species and closely related taxa. Emerging technologies like hyperspectral imagery, multi-sensor integration, and advanced machine learning hold promise for improving species-level discrimination and capturing evenness. While our findings validate H1, confirming RS as a valuable tool for ecological monitoring in stable environments, its effectiveness depends on species composition, distribution patterns, and management strategies. Addressing these limitations will enhance the potential of RS for biodiversity assessment and monitoring.</ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
                  <ce:section id="sec0095" view="all">
                     <ce:label>4.4</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="sect0115">Efficiency of RS in All species diversity analysis (H2)</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="p0255" view="all">Our findings demonstrate that RS exhibits varying levels of efficiency in assessing species diversity of canopy and understory trees across different species compositions and management categories, as validated through comparisons with FM. PERMANOVA results (Fig. A.2) and low R² values (Fig. A.3) reveal significant but varying relationships between canopy and understory diversity, suggesting that RS may not fully capture the complexity of these relationships. <ce:cross-ref id="cr0330" refid="bib51">Mestre et al. (2017)</ce:cross-ref> emphasized that understory species composition is influenced not only by the composition of the canopy layer but also by forest structure, landscape location, and micro-environmental conditions. These factors likely explain the weak correlation of Hill numbers observed between canopy and understory layers across all species compositions and management categories in the BF.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0260" view="all">In BS, RS shows low reliability for species richness (<ce:italic>q</ce:italic>=0), as confirmed by the Bland-Altman analysis (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0335" refid="fig0025">Fig. 5</ce:cross-ref>, lower panel). This is likely due to the weak correlation in species composition between the canopy and understory layers (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0340" refid="fig0020">Fig. 4</ce:cross-ref>, right panel; Fig. A.1 and A.3), further supported by significant differences observed in the PERMANOVA results (Fig. A.2). Despite missing canopy species, the overall species distribution remains relatively consistent, allowing RS to assess <ce:italic>q</ce:italic>= 1 and 2 with reasonable accuracy. However, for Shannon diversity (<ce:italic>q</ce:italic>=1) and dominance-weighted diversity (<ce:italic>q</ce:italic>=2), RS tends to slightly overestimate diversity by emphasizing canopy-dominant species while underrepresenting understory contributions. This non-significant overestimation suggests that undetected species, likely present in the understory, have a reduced impact on higher-order diversity metrics. In line with our findings, <ce:cross-ref id="cr0345" refid="bib33">Gandolfi et al. (2007)</ce:cross-ref> explain that canopy species in BS act as ecological filters, shaping the diversity of forest stands by creating specific microsite conditions that influence the regeneration and composition of the plant community beneath them.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0265" view="all">In CS, the high PERMANOVA F-value indicates substantial differences between canopy and understory species, posing challenges for RS in accurately assessing overall tree diversity. The relatively low species abundance and structural uniformity limit the ability of RS to capture diversity at the plot level, as reflected by high Bland-Altman bias (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0350" refid="fig0025">Fig. 5</ce:cross-ref>, lower panel) and elevated Bray-Curtis dissimilarity coefficients (Fig. A.9, right panel). RS still estimates diversity metrics such as Shannon (<ce:italic>q</ce:italic>=1) and dominance-weighted diversity (<ce:italic>q</ce:italic>=2) relatively well (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0355" refid="fig0020">Fig. 4</ce:cross-ref>, right panel), likely due to similarities between canopy-dominant and understory species (Fig. A.1). However, low structural complexity and the dominance of recognizable canopy species (Fig. A.8) contribute to accuracies in the accumulation curves. Although biases are evident at the plot level, RS shows potential in structurally simple environments, where homogeneous species distributions minimize spectral confusion. These findings highlight the dependency of RS on canopy visibility and species dominance patterns, making it more effective in habitats like CS, where canopy-understory differentiation is less pronounced. In MS, RS notably underestimates species richness (<ce:italic>q</ce:italic>=0) while significantly overestimating Shannon diversity (<ce:italic>q</ce:italic>=1) and dominance-weighted diversity (<ce:italic>q</ce:italic>=2). However, at the plot level, Bland-Altman analysis indicates that RS provides more reliable estimates of overall tree diversity dynamics. The structural complexity and differences in species frequency between the canopy and understory in MS (Fig. A.1) hinder the ability of RS to accurately capture higher-order Hill numbers.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0270" view="all">Across different species compositions, RS consistently underestimates species richness (<ce:italic>q</ce:italic>=0), but demonstrates improved performance for higher-order Hill numbers (<ce:italic>q</ce:italic>=1 and 2), particularly in BS and CS, with the highest accuracy observed in CS (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0360" refid="fig0020">Fig. 4</ce:cross-ref>, right panel). These findings likely reflect the fact that higher-order diversity metrics are more influenced by the relative abundances of species in canopy layers, especially in structurally simpler and compositionally homogeneous environments like CS. As emphasized by <ce:cross-ref id="cr0365" refid="bib55">Muise et al. (2024)</ce:cross-ref>, considering species composition, such as in BS, CS, and MS, is crucial for effective biodiversity monitoring. We explored the reliability of RS for estimating Hill numbers across varying species compositions, providing valuable insights into this area.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0275" view="all">RS efficiency varies significantly across management categories, with contrasting performance in SR depending on the metric used. Bray-Curtis dissimilarity shows strong compositional agreement between RS and FM for Hill numbers (Fig. A.9, right panel), but Bland-Altman analysis reveals overestimation of species richness (<ce:italic>q</ce:italic>=0) by RS at the plot level (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0370" refid="fig0025">Fig. 5</ce:cross-ref>, lower panel). This overestimation reflects inconsistencies in dominant species density estimation and the difficulties of RS in detecting less frequent species, such as rowan (0.77 individuals ha⁻¹). The low species richness in SR (10 canopy, 7 understory species) and uneven distribution (Fig. A.1 and A.8) exacerbate RS variability, particularly for Shannon (<ce:italic>q</ce:italic>=1) and dominance-weighted diversity (<ce:italic>q</ce:italic>=2) (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0375" refid="fig0020">Fig. 4</ce:cross-ref>, right panel). These findings highlight the complementary nature of the metrics used: while Bray-Curtis dissimilarity underscores the strength of RS in compositional assessments of SR, Bland-Altman agreement reveals its limitations in absolute species diversity at the plot level, emphasizing the need for multifaceted evaluations to comprehensively assess RS performance.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0280" view="all">In contrast, NR shows stronger RS reliability, with systematic bias decreasing from <ce:italic>q</ce:italic>= 0 to <ce:italic>q</ce:italic>= 2 (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0380" refid="fig0025">Fig. 5</ce:cross-ref>, lower panel). This indicates improved agreement with FM as dominant species become the focus. The balanced structure of NR, with a mix of regenerating and established species, facilitates the ability of RS to capture diversity patterns with less bias compared to SR. MF exhibits the most consistent RS performance across higher-order Hill numbers in accumulation curves, with bias reducing from <ce:italic>q</ce:italic>= 0 to <ce:italic>q</ce:italic>= 2 at the plot level, indicating near-perfect alignment with FM for dominance-weighted diversity. The stable and well-regulated environments of MF enable RS to effectively capture dominant species with minimal influence from disturbances or heterogeneity. In MF, consistent management practices likely reduce disturbances and promote a more homogeneous distribution of species. Furthermore, all 14 species were present in both the canopy and understory, contributing to this homogeneity. This uniformity may mitigate the impact of significant canopy-understory differences (Fig. A.2) on the ability of RS to reflect overall tree diversity, leading to higher reliability across all Hill numbers (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0385" refid="fig0020">Fig. 4</ce:cross-ref>, right panel).</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0285" view="all">Consistent with our observations, previous studies (<ce:cross-refs id="crs0115" refid="bib45 bib34 bib57">Knoke et al., 2008; Gao et al., 2014; Paudel and Sah, 2015</ce:cross-refs>) highlight the importance of diverse and complex canopy structures in supporting high levels of understory plant diversity. This aligns with our findings, where low diversity was observed in both the canopy and understory of SR, compared with higher diversity in both layers in MF. As noted by <ce:cross-ref id="cr0390" refid="bib1">Arasa-Gisbert et al. (2021)</ce:cross-ref> in tropical OGFs and <ce:cross-ref id="cr0395" refid="bib52">Monarrez-Gonzalez et al. (2020)</ce:cross-ref> in temperate forests, conservative management strategies can maintain species diversity, as seen in the MF of the BF. Overall, RS struggles with the low complexity of SR but performs reliably in the structured and stable conditions of NR and MF. Addressing RS limitations in SR through advanced tools like hyperspectral imaging or AI-based methods could enhance its application in these stands, while its strengths in CS and MF offers significant potential for biodiversity monitoring.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0290" view="all">The comparison of RS and FM log-scale values through RACs (<ce:cross-ref id="cr0400" refid="fig0030">Fig. 6</ce:cross-ref>) highlights how RS captures species abundance patterns across all compositions and categories. While RS often aligns with FM for dominant species, it underestimates the abundance of species like spruce, hornbeam, and pine, as seen in BS, CS, and MS. This trend is also observed in SR, NR, and MF, where species such as spruce and hornbeam consistently exhibit lower log values in RS compared with FM. Conversely, RS overestimates the rank of certain species like ash across all categories, likely due to differences in visibility or misclassification. This inevitably leads to some uncertainty in the estimates of tree species diversity. Our findings highlight both the strengths and limitations of RS in quantifying species abundance patterns. These may be partly a result of the fact that the study area is mainly composed of protected primary natural forests, and most trees have their own unique canopy niches to support their growth and regeneration strategies, enabling RS to obtain the unique spectral and structural features from visible canopies, as explained by <ce:cross-ref id="cr0405" refid="bib76">Xi et al. (2023)</ce:cross-ref>.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0295" view="all">While our 500 m² plot size follows established forest inventory standards and was appropriate for testing our hypotheses (H1 and H2), particularly regarding the reliability of RS in estimating species diversity and its relationship with canopy and understory composition; it is important to recognize potential limitations associated with this spatial scale. According to previous studies (<ce:cross-refs id="crs0120" refid="bib23 bib39 bib72 bib63 bib4">Denny and Nielsen, 2017; Hakkenberg et al., 2018; Wang and Gamon, 2019; Rocchini et al., 2022; Atkins et al., 2023</ce:cross-refs>), there is growing evidence that larger-scale sampling may better capture spatial patterns and structural heterogeneity relevant to canopy species diversity and canopy–understory relationships, particularly in complex, multi-layered forest stands. Canopy metrics derived from smaller plots may underrepresent overstory variability, potentially affecting the observed correlations with understory diversity. Future studies incorporating multi-scale designs could provide deeper insights into the spatial dynamics of species diversity and improve the integration of RS-derived canopy information with field-based understory observations.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0300" view="all">Overall, our results validate H2, confirming that RS is a reliable tool for analyzing species diversity in stable and structured contexts. However, its performance varies with species composition, particularly when considering the differing dynamics between canopy and understory layers, as well as management strategies. <ce:cross-ref id="cr0410" refid="bib63">Rocchini et al. (2022)</ce:cross-ref> emphasized that RS technologies, such as spaceborne and airborne sensors, are crucial for accurately estimating plant species diversity over large areas, highlighting the growing potential of RS in biodiversity research. At the same time, <ce:cross-ref id="cr0415" refid="bib38">Hajek et al. (2024)</ce:cross-ref> noted that studies correlating RS data with physiological parameters linked to in situ measurements remain limited. Our study takes a significant step toward addressing this gap by exploring the reliability of RS for estimating species diversity across varying contexts. The findings indicate that, in addition to the number of species, their frequency and distribution in the canopy and understory significantly affect RS reliability. Furthermore, the presence of rare species with low frequencies in the canopy and understory reduces the reliability of RS in tree species diversity assessments. This highlights the need for appropriate RS data and methodologies that can effectively distinguish between species of different and similar genera, as well as varying frequencies. By overcoming current limitations, RS can play a significant role in advancing biodiversity monitoring and conservation at broader scales, particularly by evaluating species mixtures from multiple perspectives.</ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
               </ce:section>
               <ce:section id="sec0100" role="conclusion" view="all">
                  <ce:label>5</ce:label>
                  <ce:section-title id="sect0120">Conclusions</ce:section-title>
                  <ce:para id="p0305" view="all">This study demonstrates the significant potential of RS as a tool for assessing tree species diversity across different species compositions and management strategies. Our findings highlight that RS is most effective in environments where species distributions are relatively stable and homogeneous. In stands like MS and MF, where species richness and evenness are well-balanced, RS performed reliably, providing accurate estimates of the species diversity of canopy trees and all trees, closely aligning with FM. In these contexts, the simplicity of the biodiversity patterns and the homogeneity of distribution allowed RS to accurately capture both dominance and diversity metrics, such as dominance-weighted diversity. However, the study also revealed that the effectiveness of RS diminishes in more heterogeneous stands, such as BS and SR, where species distributions are uneven and canopy and understory dynamics differ significantly. In these environments, RS struggled to fully capture the complexity of biodiversity, often underestimating species richness while overestimating abundance-weighted diversity, particularly in stands with rare species, and exhibiting discrepancies in the density estimation of dominant species. These results underscore the challenges RS faces in stands with unbalanced species distributions, disturbed habitats, or where the presence of rare species further complicates species-level identification.</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0310" view="all">The reliability of RS in tree species diversity assessment is primarily driven by its ability to detect a wide range of species, including those that are rare or occur at low frequencies, as well as accurately estimate the frequency of more abundant species. The ability of RS data and methodologies to accurately capture these species is a key factor influencing their effectiveness in biodiversity monitoring. While the weak correlation between canopy and understory diversity does play a role, its impact on the overall performance of RS is secondary to the challenges of detecting rare species and ensuring that all relevant species within the forest ecosystem are accurately represented. Despite these limitations, the RS-based direct approach remains a powerful tool for biodiversity monitoring, especially in stable, homogenous forests with relatively uniform species distributions. To overcome the challenges of detecting rare species and assessing more complex stands, future research should focus on enhancing RS methods, potentially integrating hyperspectral imagery or pre-trained machine learning techniques. These advancements could improve species-level differentiation and refine the ability of RS technologies to capture evenness, richness, and the fine-scale patterns of biodiversity, ultimately improving the accuracy of RS for forest ecosystem management and conservation efforts. In conclusion, while RS has proven to be effective in stable, homogenous environments, its limitations in more complex stands highlight the need for further development and refinement of RS technologies. With ongoing advancements, RS holds the promise of expanding the scope of biodiversity monitoring and providing critical insights for forest management and conservation strategies across diverse forest types. The continued focus on improving species identification, especially for rare and low-frequency species, will be key to unlocking the full potential of RS for ecological research and biodiversity conservation.</ce:para>
               </ce:section>
               <ce:section id="sec0105" view="all">
                  <ce:section-title id="sect0125">CRediT authorship contribution statement</ce:section-title>
                  <ce:para id="p0315" view="all">
                     <ce:bold>Maciej Lisiewicz:</ce:bold> Writing – review &amp; editing, Investigation, Formal analysis. <ce:bold>Miłosz Mielcarek:</ce:bold> Writing – review &amp; editing, Formal analysis. <ce:bold>Yousef Erfanifard:</ce:bold> Writing – original draft, Visualization, Validation, Methodology, Formal analysis, Conceptualization. <ce:bold>Bartłomiej Kraszewski:</ce:bold> Writing – review &amp; editing, Investigation, Formal analysis. <ce:bold>Krzysztof Stereńczak:</ce:bold> Writing – review &amp; editing, Validation, Conceptualization. <ce:bold>Janusz Czerepko:</ce:bold> Writing – review &amp; editing, Validation, Data curation. <ce:bold>Łukasz Kuberski:</ce:bold> Data curation.</ce:para>
               </ce:section>
            </ce:sections>
            <ce:conflict-of-interest id="coi0005" view="all">
               <ce:section-title id="sect0130">Declaration of Competing Interest</ce:section-title>
               <ce:para id="p0320" view="all">The authors declare that they have no known competing financial interests or personal relationships that could have appeared to influence the work reported in this paper.</ce:para>
            </ce:conflict-of-interest>
            <ce:acknowledgment id="ack0005" view="all">
               <ce:section-title id="sect0135">Acknowledgements</ce:section-title>
               <ce:para id="p0325" view="all">This research was undertaken in collaboration between Forest Research Institute (IBL), Poland, and IDEAS NCBR, Poland. We would like to express our gratitude to IDEAS NCBR for their invaluable contribution to this research project, made possible through a scholarship granted to Y.E. Remote sensing data acquisition and field data collection from Białowieża Forest were conducted as part of the project “Assessment and monitoring of biodiversity of the Białowieża Forest based on selected natural elements – continuation”, funded by the <ce:grant-sponsor id="gs1" xlink:type="simple" xlink:role="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/linking-roles/grant-sponsor">General Directorate of the State Forests in Warsaw</ce:grant-sponsor> (contract number <ce:grant-number refid="gs1">MZ.271.3.7.2022</ce:grant-number>, internal no. <ce:grant-number refid="gs1">500483</ce:grant-number>).</ce:para>
            </ce:acknowledgment>
            <ce:appendices view="all">
               <ce:section id="sec0110" view="compact-standard">
                  <ce:label>Appendix A</ce:label>
                  <ce:section-title id="sect0140">Supporting information</ce:section-title>
                  <ce:para id="p0330" view="all">Supplementary data associated with this article can be found in the online version at <ce:inter-ref id="ir0005" xlink:href="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.foreco.2025.122987" xlink:type="simple">doi:10.1016/j.foreco.2025.122987</ce:inter-ref>.</ce:para>
               </ce:section>
               <ce:section id="sec0115" view="extended">
